EP  - 295
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(92)90088-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407692900889
AB  - When the prior is only partially specified, it is sometimes possible to ‘estimate’ its unspecified part by maximizing the predictive density (marginal likelihood) of the data. This paper examines the usefulness and the limitations of the priors of this kind (HPRD priors) and the corresponding posterior mean (HPRD estimators) in a regression setup. The HPRD estimator turns out to be a simple shrinkage estimator, and it is found that there is an interesting relationship, regarding the shrinkage factor of an estimator, between the empirical Bayes approach and the HPRD approach. The latter findings may provide some insight into getting the right size of shrinkage to attain the minimum risk. The HPRD prior can rarely serve as a reference prior, however, since the prior information it contains is too strong. Although this shortcoming is partly due to the nature of the HPRD approach itself, it can sometimes be alleviated by a more careful choice of the class of priors. If the lower bound on the prior variance is set correctly, the HPRD estimator will provide a sensible candidate for the point estimate of the regression coefficients. We also show a link between the HPRD approach and the lower bound on the Bayes factor.
ER  - 

